    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-04T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-04T13:00:00-05:00" n="962"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d962">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/16712: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-04T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 4, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>371. Chungking’s 263, June 30, 10 a.m.<note n="46" xml:id="d962fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> The Department desires that if this has not already been
                    done there be filed with the Ministry of Foreign Affairs a strong protest
                    against this latest reported instance of the imperiling of the American Embassy
                    through bombing operations at Chungking.<note n="47" xml:id="d962fn2">For
                        Ambassador Grew’s note No. 1845, July 8, see <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v01#pg_718">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 718</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Department regards this renewed bombing in a place so near to the Embassy
                    premises as to cause damage to the staff residence as the more reprehensible
                    following so soon after the assurances given in the Foreign Office note of June
                    18 (see your 851, June 19, 9 p.m.<note n="48" xml:id="d962fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_717">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 717</ref>.</note>).</p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo via Shanghai. Repeated to Chungking, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
